I don't use #eHailing (or any other public transport) very much myself, because I'm fortunate to have people in my support system who can drive and are generally available to take me where I need to go. But I know that plenty of my visually impaired peers use it quite often.

These regulations are ostensibly aimed at improving safety for riders in South Africa: https://techcentral.co.za/the-sweeping-changes-coming-to-e-hailing-in-south-africa/271881/?utm_source=MastodonAfrica

I think safety's a good thing, but I'm concerned about the requirement that all vehicles used for e-hailing be branded on both sides of the car, because I know one or two people who drive for Uber and Bolt, and to my mind, the whole point of doing so is to make a little extra money on the side. Drivers use their personal vehicles, and they can decide if and when they're available for work, and which company they're driving for. The fact that, when they're not actively working, they don't necessarily have to make it known that they *do* drive for Uber/Bolt is a big plus (of course, they do have to display their PDP in the windshield, but that's fairly unobtrusive, and could mean anything).

It's also why I'm kinda against making these drivers full-time employees, with all the benefits -- and restrictions -- that that implies, because they're NOT full-time employees; they do lots of different things.

So... yeah, I dunno. What do you think? #SouthAfrica
